<taxonomicName id="4C24ECD9754BD70F8D4EFD215AA4FD52" baseAuthorityName="Schreber" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[2132,2266,718,751]" class="Mammalia" family="Nycteridae" genus="Nycteris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="384" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hispida">N. hispida</taxonomicName>
. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33EC4D1754BD70F8D14FD1A5842FCD8" pageId="4" pageNumber="384" type="distribution">
<caption id="DF5BC7D2754BD70F8D14FD1A5842FCD8" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6576956" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6576956" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6576956/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="384" targetBox="[1447,2039,567,980]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph id="8B9B975A754BD70F8D14FD1A5842FCD8" blockId="4.[2062,2656,568,987]" pageId="4" pageNumber="384">
<emphasis id="B9504B48754BD70F8D14FD1A5AC1FCAB" bold="true" box="[2062,2239,757,790]" pageId="4" pageNumber="384">Distribution.</emphasis>
Patchily distributed in savannas of E Africa including 
<collectingCountry id="F333D7CA754BD70F8C9CFCF35B89FC80" box="[2438,2551,796,829]" name="Somalia" pageId="4" pageNumber="384">Somalia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F333D7CA754BD70F8F11FCF35A44FCD8" name="Ethiopia" pageId="4" pageNumber="384">Ethiopia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F333D7CA754BD70F8D51FCA75B7FFCD8" box="[2123,2305,840,869]" name="South Sudan" pageId="4" pageNumber="384">South Sudan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F333D7CA754BD70F8C08FCA75B17FCD8" box="[2322,2409,840,869]" name="Kenya" pageId="4" pageNumber="384">Kenya</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="F333D7CA754BD70F8CADFCA75849FCD8" box="[2487,2615,840,869]" name="Tanzania" pageId="4" pageNumber="384">Tanzania</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33EC4D1754BD70F8D14FC8454ABFB22" pageId="4" pageNumber="384" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B9B975A754BD70F8D14FC8454ABFB22" blockId="4.[2062,2656,568,987]" lastBlockId="4.[1447,2655,993,1538]" pageId="4" pageNumber="384">
<emphasis id="B9504B48754BD70F8D14FC845B76FC31" bold="true" box="[2062,2312,875,908]" pageId="4" pageNumber="384">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 40-50 mm, tail 45-56 mm, ear 25-31 mm, hindfoot 10-11 mm, forearm 37-45 mm; weight 6-12 g. Andersen’s Slit-faced Batis small, with short rounded wings. Longitudinal cleft runs along top of muzzle, covering noseleaves. Furis long and fluffy, medium to dark brown dorsally, and slightly lighter ventrally. Ears are very long but of medium length for a slitfaced bat. Wing membranes are dark brown. There are no obvious sexual differences in pelage.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33EC4D1754BD70F80B3FB495B83FB7A" box="[1449,2557,1190,1223]" pageId="4" pageNumber="384" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B9B975A754BD70F80B3FB495B83FB7A" blockId="4.[1447,2655,993,1538]" box="[1449,2557,1190,1223]" pageId="4" pageNumber="384">
<emphasis id="B9504B48754BD70F80B3FB495466FB7A" bold="true" box="[1449,1560,1190,1223]" pageId="4" pageNumber="384">Habitat.</emphasis>
Savanna and open woodland, coastal forests, and coconut plantations.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
